Introduction¶

Dataset Description:¶

This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

A clean version of the dataset can be downloaded from this link. (cleaned from original data on Kaggle)

The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Dataset issues:¶

Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column.

Explored questions:¶

In this report we will find an answer to the following two research questions:

  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • Is there a correlation between movie popularity and revenue?
  • Is there a correlation between movie vote average and revenue?

The dataset has many columns, from which the following are the important to our analysis:

  • id: unique identifier of the movie.
  • popularity: Reference
  • genres : Movie genres.
  • release_year: Movie release year.
  • budget_adj: The budget of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.
  • revenue_adj: The revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

They are irrelevant for our analysis. So, we can safely drop them.

Rows of the dataset that contain zero or missing values are a large portion of the dataset. So, we create separate copies of the dataset for each research question with those rows removed.

correlation : (0.6090834322818585, 0.0)

A correlation coefficient of 0.609 indicate a moderate correlation between popularity and revenue.

Research Question 3 : Is there a correlation between movie vote average and revenue?¶

In [27]:
#df_q2.plot.scatter('vote_average', 'revenue_adj',c='blue');

ax = df_q2.plot.scatter(
    'vote_average',
    'revenue_adj',
    c='red',
    title = 'Correlation Between Vote Average and Revenue',
    figsize=(10,5)
    );

ax.set_xlabel('Vote Average');
ax.set_ylabel('Revenue Adjusted (2010 dollars)');

print("correlation :", scipy.stats.pearsonr(df.vote_average, df.revenue_adj))

correlation : (0.1930850948330119, 9.21692126148123e-92)

A correlation coefficient of 0.19 indicate a none or very weak correlation between popularity and revenue.

Conclusions¶

The dataset contains the data of 10866 movies. This number is good for a movie database and can represent the whole population.

The popularity of gernes from year to year was analyzied by calculating the mean of popularity for each genre for years from 1960 to 2010. It was found that the three genres Adventure, Animation and Fantasy were the most popular three genres for all the years.

To measure the relationship between revenue and both popularity and voting average the pearson correlation test was used. The correlation test was made betwen popularity and revenue and was found to be 0.60 indicating a moderate correlation. It was also tested for the relationship between voting average and revenue and was measured 0.19 indicating weak or non-existent correlation.

Limitations¶

The dataset has some limitations:

  • Missing genres : Some movies that have missing genres (23 rows of 10866) but it was easily neglecgted and such a small number didn't affect our analysis of popularity of genres much.
  • Zero revenue It has large count of rows with missing (zero) revenue values (6016 of 10866), which is a large percentage for such a dataset (55%). Such large percentage of missing values affects the analysis of the relationship between popularity and revenue, and voting average and revenue. Those data points were removed as they could not be completed.
  • Zero budget values. removing such values in addtion to zero revenue values would make analysis of the relationship between budget and revenue not very accurate.
  • Certain columns, like cast and genres, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. The genres required significant work to prepare them for a analysis.
  • Ambiguous popularity metric. Not enough details about how it was calculated.
